<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
  Surfaced by <a href="/backlog/779-temporal-trait-impl-locus-we-blocks-vs-frontierui-blocks/">#779</a>:
  implementers building WE-compatible libraries will eventually need a generic service to validate their
  schema/manifest against the WE contract. The artifact <strong>forks by risk</strong>. The conformance
  <strong>vectors</strong> (declarative input&nbsp;→&nbsp;expected-behavior data) are a WE artifact — data
  can't "fail to deliver." The runnable <strong>validator</strong> that loads them and checks a library is
  <strong>not</strong> WE (the user flagged a reputational risk: a big runnable tool that slips reads as
  "WE is broken," and moving only the npm scope doesn't fix it — ownership carries the reputation) and
  <strong>not</strong> FUI (it's generic across implementers, FUI is one). This survey grounds
  <a href="/backlog/895-home-for-a-generic-we-conformance-schema-validation-service-/">#895</a>:
  <strong>where does the runnable validator live</strong> — an independent open devtool repo, a Plateau-suite
  open-core offering, or hosted by WE itself?
</p>

<h2>What the survey found</h2>
<p>
  The dominant pattern across real conformance tooling is a <strong>two-layer split nobody violates</strong>:
  the standards body owns the <em>vectors/suite</em> as neutral data in its own repo, and the
  <em>runnable validator is decoupled from the body</em>, almost always as OSS. Where a runnable tool ships,
  the field splits into two live shapes — both anchored on a <em>complete open floor</em> — plus a third
  (body-hosted) that re-attaches validator bugs to the standard and is the one to avoid for a young standard.
</p>

