<h3>2 · The reputational firewall</h3>
<p>
  The decoupling <em>is</em> the firewall: when the runner isn't the body's artifact, a runner bug is
  unambiguously the runner's and the spec stays clean (test262's "no preference given by Ecma to any runner"
  is the canonical statement). The standards-body-hosted model (Nu Html Checker) deliberately makes the body
  wear the validator's bugs — tolerable only because HTML is mature, the checker is a single canonical
  artifact, and the code is self-hostable. For a young standard it's the model to avoid, which restates the
  user's "not WE" concern from the survey side.
</p>

<h2>What survives</h2>
<p>
  <strong>One forced invariant set + one genuine fork.</strong> Invariants: (a) vectors → WE as a separate
  <code>@webeverything/…</code> data package (the neutral SoT, in WE's repo); the validator is (b)
  <strong>not</strong> WE-hosted and (c) <strong>not</strong> FUI; and (d) whatever its home, the open CLI must
  be a <em>complete standalone conformance floor</em> (the Spectral/axe-core test — runs with zero
  account/license; any hosted tier adds hosting/reporting/collaboration only). The fork is the validator's
  <strong>home</strong>: a <strong>Plateau-suite open-core offering</strong> (free CLI floor + optional hosted
  Plateau service) vs an <strong>independent open devtool repo</strong>.
</p>
<p>
  <strong>Recommended default: Plateau open-core (~75%).</strong> Pure independent OSS is the <em>strongest</em>
  decoupling but presumes a community materializes to build + maintain the runner — which a pre-community,
  solo-dev standard won't get, leaving vectors with no runner. Vendor open-core <em>guarantees</em> a runner
  exists without re-coupling reputation to WE — provided the two structural invariants hold — and aligns with
  the constellation's product layering (<a href="/backlog/091-managed-offering-constellation-layering/">#091</a>
  served-product → plateau-app; <a href="/backlog/475-vision-is-a-plateau-service/">#475</a> impl capability =
  Plateau service WE consumes) and the open-core line drawn on the <em>cost/hosting</em> axis, never
  open-vs-proprietary. <strong>Residual (~25%):</strong> in a single-constellation setup, if Plateau is
  perceived as the de-facto owner of WE, a validator bug can still splash onto the standard despite the formal
  split; mitigation is the two invariants applied structurally (permissive license, self-hostable, forkable;
  vectors in the WE repo). If a genuine multi-implementer community ever forms, an independent
  neutral-governance repo becomes the correct override.
</p>
